The wreckage of ''Macon'' was listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on 29 January 2010.<ref name="newlistings2010feb12"/> The location of the wreck site remains secret and is within a [[marine sanctuary]], the [[Monterey Bay National Marine Sanctuary]]. It is not accessible to divers due to depth ({{Convert|1500|ft|abbr=on|disp=or}}).<ref name="nrhpreg">{{cite web |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: USS Macon |url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/feature/weekly_features/USSMacon.pdf |format=PDF |date=10 February 2009 |author=Bruce G. Terrell |publisher=[[National Park Service]] |accessdate=2010-05-18}} (39 pages, with 20 historic and wreckage exploration photos)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanctuaries.noaa.gov/missions/2006macon/welcome.html |title=2006 USS Macon Expedition |publisher=Sanctuaries.noaa.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/stories2006/s2708.htm |title=NOAA News Online (Story 2708) |publisher=Noaanews.noaa.gov |date=27 September 2006 |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref>

The U.S. National Park Service states:<ref name=highlight>{{cite web|title=Weekly Highlight 02/12/2010 USS ''Macon'' Airship Remains, Monterey County, California | url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/feature/weekly_features/10_02_12_USS_Macon.htm}}</ref>

{{quote |When the USS ''Macon'' was christened on 11 March 1933 the rigid airship was the most sophisticated of the Navy<U+2019>s lighter-than-air (LTA) fleet. The ''Macon'' exhibited the highest expression of naval LTA technology during the ship's short career. At 785 feet in length, the airship<U+2019>s size captured American fascination during flyovers of U.S. communities as chronicled in numerous advertisements, articles, and newsreels. The dramatic loss of the ''Macon'' and sister ship {{USS|Akron|ZRS-4|2}} within two years of each other contributed to the cancellation of the Navy<U+2019>s rigid airship program. The archeological remains of the USS ''Macon'' lie off California<U+2019>s Big Sur coast in NOAA<U+2019>s [[Monterey Bay National Marine Sanctuary]]. The site also contains the remains of four of the airship<U+2019>s squadron of small Curtiss [[F9C Sparrowhawk]] scout aircraft which the ''Macon'' carried in an internal hangar bay.}}

The site was listed on the U.S. [[National Register of Historic Places]] on 29 January 2010.<ref name="newlistings2010feb12"/> The listing was announced as the featured listing in the [[National Park Service]]'s weekly list of 12 February 2010.<ref name="featured">{{cite web | url = http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/nrlist.htm | title = Weekly List Actions | accessdate = 2010-05-18 | work = | publisher = National Park Service }}</ref>

==In popular fiction==

The ''Macon'' is featured as a setting and key plot element in Max McCoy's novel ''[[Indiana Jones and the Philosopher's Stone]]''; [[Indiana Jones]] travels aboard the ''Macon'' while it makes a [[transatlantic flight|transatlantic]] flight to [[London, England|London]].

